modules.name: AWS.Lightsail
modules.comments:
Amazon Lightsail is the easiest way to get started with AWS for developers who just need virtual private servers. Lightsail includes everything you need to launch your project quickly - a virtual machine, SSD-based storage, data transfer, DNS management, and a static IP - for a low, predictable price. You manage those Lightsail servers through the Lightsail console or by using the API or command-line interface (CLI).

For more information about Lightsail concepts and tasks, see the Lightsail Dev Guide.

To use the Lightsail API or the CLI, you will need to use AWS Identity and Access Management (IAM) to generate access keys. For details about how to set this up, see the Lightsail Dev Guide.

declarations.comments: Allocates a static IP address.
declarations.title: allocateStaticIp

declarations.comments: Attaches a block storage disk to a running or stopped Lightsail instance and exposes it to the instance with the specified disk name.
declarations.title: attachDisk

declarations.comments: Attaches one or more Lightsail instances to a load balancer.
declarations.title: attachInstancesToLoadBalancer

declarations.comments:
Attaches a Transport Layer Security (TLS) certificate to your load balancer.

TLS is just an updated, more secure version of Secure Socket Layer (SSL).
declarations.title: attachLoadBalancerTlsCertificate

declarations.comments: Attaches a static IP address to a specific Amazon Lightsail instance.
declarations.title: attachStaticIp

declarations.comments: Closes the public ports on a specific Amazon Lightsail instance.
declarations.title: closeInstancePublicPorts

declarations.comments: Creates a block storage disk that can be attached to a Lightsail instance in the same Availability Zone (e.g., us-east-2a). The disk is created in the regional endpoint that you send the HTTP request to. For more information, see Regions and Availability Zones in Lightsail.
declarations.title: createDisk

declarations.comments: Creates a block storage disk from a disk snapshot that can be attached to a Lightsail instance in the same Availability Zone (e.g., us-east-2a). The disk is created in the regional endpoint that you send the HTTP request to. For more information, see Regions and Availability Zones in Lightsail.
declarations.title: createDiskFromSnapshot

declarations.comments:
Creates a snapshot of a block storage disk. You can use snapshots for backups, to make copies of disks, and to save data before shutting down a Lightsail instance.

You can take a snapshot of an attached disk that is in use; however, snapshots only capture data that has been written to your disk at the time the snapshot command is issued. This may exclude any data that has been cached by any applications or the operating system. If you can pause any file systems on the disk long enough to take a snapshot, your snapshot should be complete. Nevertheless, if you cannot pause all file writes to the disk, you should unmount the disk from within the Lightsail instance, issue the create disk snapshot command, and then remount the disk to ensure a consistent and complete snapshot. You may remount and use your disk while the snapshot status is pending.
declarations.title: createDiskSnapshot

declarations.comments: Creates a domain resource for the specified domain (e.g., example.com).
declarations.title: createDomain

declarations.comments: Creates one of the following entry records associated with the domain: A record, CNAME record, TXT record, or MX record.
declarations.title: createDomainEntry

declarations.comments: Creates a snapshot of a specific virtual private server, or instance. You can use a snapshot to create a new instance that is based on that snapshot.
declarations.title: createInstanceSnapshot

declarations.comments: Creates one or more Amazon Lightsail virtual private servers, or instances.
declarations.title: createInstances

declarations.comments: Uses a specific snapshot as a blueprint for creating one or more new instances that are based on that identical configuration.
declarations.title: createInstancesFromSnapshot

declarations.comments: Creates sn SSH key pair.
declarations.title: createKeyPair

declarations.comments:
Creates a Lightsail load balancer.

When you create a load balancer, you can specify certificates and port settings. You can create up to 5 load balancers per AWS Region in your account.
declarations.title: createLoadBalancer

declarations.comments:
Creates a Lightsail load balancer TLS certificate.

TLS is just an updated, more secure version of Secure Socket Layer (SSL).
declarations.title: createLoadBalancerTlsCertificate

declarations.comments:
Deletes the specified block storage disk. The disk must be in the available state (not attached to a Lightsail instance).

The disk may remain in the deleting state for several minutes.
declarations.title: deleteDisk

declarations.comments:
Deletes the specified disk snapshot.

When you make periodic snapshots of a disk, the snapshots are incremental, and only the blocks on the device that have changed since your last snapshot are saved in the new snapshot. When you delete a snapshot, only the data not needed for any other snapshot is removed. So regardless of which prior snapshots have been deleted, all active snapshots will have access to all the information needed to restore the disk.
declarations.title: deleteDiskSnapshot

declarations.comments: Deletes the specified domain recordset and all of its domain records.
declarations.title: deleteDomain

declarations.comments: Deletes a specific domain entry.
declarations.title: deleteDomainEntry

declarations.comments: Deletes a specific Amazon Lightsail virtual private server, or instance.
declarations.title: deleteInstance

declarations.comments: Deletes a specific snapshot of a virtual private server (or instance).
declarations.title: deleteInstanceSnapshot

declarations.comments: Deletes a specific SSH key pair.
declarations.title: deleteKeyPair

declarations.comments: Deletes a Lightsail load balancer.
declarations.title: deleteLoadBalancer

declarations.comments: Deletes a TLS/SSL certificate associated with a Lightsail load balancer.
declarations.title: deleteLoadBalancerTlsCertificate

declarations.comments: Detaches a stopped block storage disk from a Lightsail instance. Make sure to unmount any file systems on the device within your operating system before stopping the instance and detaching the disk.
declarations.title: detachDisk

declarations.comments: Detaches the specified instances from a Lightsail load balancer.
declarations.title: detachInstancesFromLoadBalancer

declarations.comments: Detaches a static IP from the Amazon Lightsail instance to which it is attached.
declarations.title: detachStaticIp

declarations.comments: Downloads the default SSH key pair from the user's account.
declarations.title: downloadDefaultKeyPair

declarations.comments: Returns the names of all active (not deleted) resources.
declarations.title: getActiveNames

declarations.comments: Returns the list of available instance images, or blueprints. You can use a blueprint to create a new virtual private server already running a specific operating system, as well as a preinstalled app or development stack. The software each instance is running depends on the blueprint image you choose.
declarations.title: getBlueprints

declarations.comments: Returns the list of bundles that are available for purchase. A bundle describes the specs for your virtual private server (or instance).
declarations.title: getBundles

declarations.comments: Returns information about a specific block storage disk.
declarations.title: getDisk

declarations.comments: Returns information about a specific block storage disk snapshot.
declarations.title: getDiskSnapshot

declarations.comments:
Returns information about all block storage disk snapshots in your AWS account and region.

If you are describing a long list of disk snapshots, you can paginate the output to make the list more manageable. You can use the pageToken and nextPageToken values to retrieve the next items in the list.
declarations.title: getDiskSnapshots

declarations.comments:
Returns information about all block storage disks in your AWS account and region.

If you are describing a long list of disks, you can paginate the output to make the list more manageable. You can use the pageToken and nextPageToken values to retrieve the next items in the list.
declarations.title: getDisks

declarations.comments: Returns information about a specific domain recordset.
declarations.title: getDomain

declarations.comments: Returns a list of all domains in the user's account.
declarations.title: getDomains

declarations.comments: Returns information about a specific Amazon Lightsail instance, which is a virtual private server.
declarations.title: getInstance

declarations.comments: Returns temporary SSH keys you can use to connect to a specific virtual private server, or instance.
declarations.title: getInstanceAccessDetails

declarations.comments: Returns the data points for the specified Amazon Lightsail instance metric, given an instance name.
declarations.title: getInstanceMetricData

declarations.comments: Returns the port states for a specific virtual private server, or instance.
declarations.title: getInstancePortStates

declarations.comments: Returns information about a specific instance snapshot.
declarations.title: getInstanceSnapshot

declarations.comments: Returns all instance snapshots for the user's account.
declarations.title: getInstanceSnapshots

declarations.comments: Returns the state of a specific instance. Works on one instance at a time.
declarations.title: getInstanceState

declarations.comments: Returns information about all Amazon Lightsail virtual private servers, or instances.
declarations.title: getInstances

declarations.comments: Returns information about a specific key pair.
declarations.title: getKeyPair

declarations.comments: Returns information about all key pairs in the user's account.
declarations.title: getKeyPairs

declarations.comments: Returns information about the specified Lightsail load balancer.
declarations.title: getLoadBalancer

declarations.comments: Returns information about health metrics for your Lightsail load balancer.
declarations.title: getLoadBalancerMetricData

declarations.comments:
Returns information about the TLS certificates that are associated with the specified Lightsail load balancer.

TLS is just an updated, more secure version of Secure Socket Layer (SSL).
declarations.title: getLoadBalancerTlsCertificates

declarations.comments:
Returns information about all load balancers in an account.

If you are describing a long list of load balancers, you can paginate the output to make the list more manageable. You can use the pageToken and nextPageToken values to retrieve the next items in the list.
declarations.title: getLoadBalancers

declarations.comments: Returns information about a specific operation. Operations include events such as when you create an instance, allocate a static IP, attach a static IP, and so on.
declarations.title: getOperation

declarations.comments:
Returns information about all operations.

Results are returned from oldest to newest, up to a maximum of 200. Results can be paged by making each subsequent call to GetOperations use the maximum (last) statusChangedAt value from the previous request.
declarations.title: getOperations

declarations.comments: Gets operations for a specific resource (e.g., an instance or a static IP).
declarations.title: getOperationsForResource

declarations.comments: Returns a list of all valid regions for Amazon Lightsail. Use the include availability zones parameter to also return the availability zones in a region.
declarations.title: getRegions

declarations.comments: Returns information about a specific static IP.
declarations.title: getStaticIp

declarations.comments: Returns information about all static IPs in the user's account.
declarations.title: getStaticIps

declarations.comments: Imports a public SSH key from a specific key pair.
declarations.title: importKeyPair

declarations.comments: Returns a Boolean value indicating whether your Lightsail VPC is peered.
declarations.title: isVpcPeered

declarations.comments: Adds public ports to an Amazon Lightsail instance.
declarations.title: openInstancePublicPorts

declarations.comments: Tries to peer the Lightsail VPC with the user's default VPC.
declarations.title: peerVpc

declarations.comments: Sets the specified open ports for an Amazon Lightsail instance, and closes all ports for every protocol not included in the current request.
declarations.title: putInstancePublicPorts

declarations.comments: Restarts a specific instance. When your Amazon Lightsail instance is finished rebooting, Lightsail assigns a new public IP address. To use the same IP address after restarting, create a static IP address and attach it to the instance.
declarations.title: rebootInstance

declarations.comments: Deletes a specific static IP from your account.
declarations.title: releaseStaticIp

declarations.comments: Starts a specific Amazon Lightsail instance from a stopped state. To restart an instance, use the reboot instance operation.
declarations.title: startInstance

declarations.comments: Stops a specific Amazon Lightsail instance that is currently running.
declarations.title: stopInstance

declarations.comments: Attempts to unpeer the Lightsail VPC from the user's default VPC.
declarations.title: unpeerVpc

declarations.comments: Updates a domain recordset after it is created.
declarations.title: updateDomainEntry

declarations.comments: Updates the specified attribute for a load balancer.
declarations.title: updateLoadBalancerAttribute

Lightsail throws this exception when user input does not conform to the validation rules of an input field.

Domain-related APIs are only available in the N. Virginia (us-east-1) Region. Please set your Region configuration to us-east-1 to create, view, or edit these resources.
